# Cloudflare Workers Rules

## Runtime Constraints
- Workers run in the V8 isolate runtime, NOT Node.js
- CPU time limit: 10ms on free tier (wall-clock time for `fetch()` does not count, but computation does)
- No Node.js built-ins: no `fs`, no `path`, no `crypto` (use Web Crypto API instead)
- No `require()` — use ES module imports only
- No Puppeteer, no Playwright, no Chrome DevTools Protocol
- Bundle size limit: 3 MB compressed on free tier, 10 MB on paid ($5/mo)

## HTML Parsing
- Use `HTMLRewriter` for streaming HTML parsing — it is the native CF Worker API
- Do NOT use `cheerio`, `jsdom`, or any DOM library — they pull in Node.js APIs
- HTMLRewriter is streaming: process elements as they arrive, do not buffer the full response

## Fetch / HTTP
- ALL outbound fetches to user-submitted URLs MUST pass through `validateUrl()` from `../lib/ssrf`
- Set `redirect: 'manual'` on all fetches that follow user-supplied URLs
- Re-validate redirect target URLs through `validateUrl()` before following
- Set a timeout on all external fetches: wrap with `Promise.race` and a `AbortController`
- Default fetch timeout: 10 seconds for scan requests

## SSRF Prevention (non-negotiable)
```typescript
// Always do this before fetching a user-submitted URL:
import { validateUrl } from '../lib/ssrf';

const validation = await validateUrl(userSuppliedUrl);
if (!validation.ok) {
  return new Response(JSON.stringify({ error: validation.reason }), { status: 400 });
}
const response = await fetch(validation.safeUrl, { redirect: 'manual' });
```

## Rate Limiting
- Use the native CF Workers Rate Limiting binding: `env.RATE_LIMITER.limit({ key: clientIp })`
- Default: 10 requests/minute per IP on the scan endpoint
- Block IPs making >20 scan requests per day (write to KV)
- Always read the `CF-Connecting-IP` header, not `X-Forwarded-For` (CF strips/replaces it)

## Cloudflare Queues
- Enqueue deep audit jobs on payment confirmation — never process synchronously in the webhook handler
- Consumer Worker retries up to 3 times with exponential backoff
- Dead-letter queue: write failed jobs to KV with error details, trigger Resend alert email
- Always acknowledge queue messages: return from the handler (implicit ack) or throw to retry

## Secrets and Environment
- ALL secrets come from `env` bindings — they are injected at runtime
- Never access `process.env` in Workers — use the typed `Env` interface
- Define the `Env` interface at the top of every Worker entry file:

```typescript
export interface Env {
  SUPABASE_URL: string;
  SUPABASE_SERVICE_ROLE_KEY: string;
  STRIPE_WEBHOOK_SECRET: string;
  GEMINI_API_KEY: string;
  RESEND_API_KEY: string;
  TURNSTILE_SECRET_KEY: string;
  SCAN_QUEUE: Queue;
  RATE_LIMITER: RateLimit;
  SCAN_CACHE: KVNamespace;
}
```

## PDF Generation
- Use `pdf-lib` — it is pure JavaScript and runs in Workers
- Do NOT use jsPDF (low quality output)
- Do NOT use Satori (may exceed 10ms CPU limit on free tier)
- Keep PDF generation within the paid Workers plan ($5/mo) — the 10ms free-tier CPU limit WILL break PDF generation
- Generate PDFs in the Queue consumer Worker, not in the request handler

## Gemini API
- Gemini is called for EXACTLY TWO checks: Q&A block detection and extractability scoring
- All other audit checks are deterministic — no AI required
- Wrap all Gemini calls with a try/catch; on failure, mark the check as "unable to assess" (do not fail the entire audit)
- The Gemini provider (model name + endpoint) MUST be a config variable, not hardcoded:
```typescript
const GEMINI_MODEL = env.GEMINI_MODEL ?? 'gemini-2.5-flash-lite-preview-06-17';
```
- Respect 1,000 RPD free tier limit — add request queuing if approaching limit

## Stripe Webhooks
- ALWAYS verify the `Stripe-Signature` header before processing any webhook:
```typescript
const event = stripe.webhooks.constructEvent(rawBody, sig, env.STRIPE_WEBHOOK_SECRET);
```
- Reject unverified events with 400 — never process without signature verification
- Handle idempotency: check if the Stripe event ID has already been processed (store in Supabase)
- Only act on `checkout.session.completed` and `invoice.payment_succeeded` — ignore all others silently

## Turnstile Validation
- Validate Turnstile tokens server-side before processing any scan request:
```typescript
const turnstileUrl = 'https://challenges.cloudflare.com/turnstile/v0/siteverify';
const result = await fetch(turnstileUrl, {
  method: 'POST',
  body: JSON.stringify({ secret: env.TURNSTILE_SECRET_KEY, response: token }),
  headers: { 'Content-Type': 'application/json' },
});
const data = await result.json();
if (!data.success) return new Response('Bot detected', { status: 403 });
```
